com.itko.lisa.test

Class TestEvent

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.itko.lisa.test.TestEvent
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable

    public class TestEvent
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.io.Serializable
    This object contains all the data related to a specific event that occurred during a test execution. It is the communication packet that flows from simulators to the event listeners that will log the data, make calculations, and etc.

    There are a number of functions provided in this class. See individual data and method content for more. Briefly:

    • Test Event IDs - constants for every built-in event type
    • Test Event Names - string constants for the names and a method to convert an ID to a name
    • Filters - a set of default filters that enable easier use of the filter mechanism

      Filters are an array of Event IDs that you will NOT get when used with the TestEventMgr.

    See Also:
    TestEventMgr, TestEventListener, Serialized Form

        public static final java.lang.String[] eventFields

      • eventNames

        public static final java.lang.String[] eventNames
        There are the human names for the event ids for convenient logging Another use of these names is that each can be defined in the current test execution state (basically, it is the key of a property), and a boolean associated with it that answers the question "Do you want this event ignored?" The default for all built-in events is that they ARE FILTERED, meaning that they will not be published.

        By the way, there is another filtering mechanism per listener that is set when a listener registers with the manager.

        See Also:
        TestEventMgr

        public static final int EVENT_NORMALEND
        This Event ID indicates that this test execution completed in a successful state. You will get either EVENT_NORMALEND, EVENT_CANNOT_FINISH, EVENT_ABEND, or EVENT_STOPTESTSIGNAL in any normal situation to indicate the instance is finished.

      • EVENT_ABEND

        public static final int EVENT_ABEND
        This Event ID indicates that this test execution failed. Should mean that there are no exceptions in the test case, but either logic errors in the test case or in the system under test caused the test case not to complete as expected. You will get either EVENT_NORMALEND, EVENT_ABEND, EVENT_CANNOT_FINISH, or EVENT_STOPTESTSIGNAL in any normal situation to indicate the cycle is finished.
        See Also:

        This event is fired when a Result node has been asserted. This happens when each result is compared to the response we got from the system under test, and the result shown in the shortDesc field is true. That means that this result was found, and will fire (ie., determine the next node to exec)

        public static final int EVENT_NODERESPONSE
        This Event ID indicates that we have completed a transaction against the system under test. The node we executed is in the short description field, and the result data is in the long description field. (This can be quite large, so treat it carefully!)
        See Also:
        Constant Field Values

      • EVENT_EXECTIME

        public static final int EVENT_EXECTIME
        This Event ID records the amount of time a transaction took to execute against the system under test. It attempts to tease apart prep time on the part of LISA and considers just the time it takes to construct the connection, send, and receieve the full result.

        If the node is quiet then we do NOT publish this event.

        See Also:
        Constant Field Values

      • EVENT_BANDWIDTH

        public static final int EVENT_BANDWIDTH
        This event will approximate how much data was sent and received from the system under test for a given node's execution. It reports its actual bytes sent to the OS but does not attempt to predict expansion due to packetizing, headers, and etc. So it is a fairly accurate but not precise measure

        If the node is quiet then we do NOT publish this event.

        See Also:
        Constant Field Values

      • EVENT_ERROR

        public static final int EVENT_ERROR
        This event occurs when the Node believes that an error has ocurred not as a result of a test case error but b/c of an error in the system under test.

        For example, getting no response at all back from a web server should report this event instead of the EVENT_EXECTIME, BANDWIDTH, and RESPONSE

        Note that as of LISA5 there is an additional event for errors in ways that mean we could not actually run the node's logic. An example here is a 404 error code from the WS or an inability to lookup the service via UDDI.

        See Also:

        public static final int EVENT_TESTDEFERROR

      • makeFilterGetOnly

        public static int[] makeFilterGetOnly(int[] theseEvents)

        Parameters:

        Returns:

      • isFailureEvent

        public boolean isFailureEvent()
        There are a variety of event types that can notify that a specific node or whole test has failed. If there is an unexpected problem with the test itself, you will see an EVENT_TESTDEFERROR or EVENT_TESTRUNERROR. If one node of a test fails you will see an EVENT_ERROR. And if a whole test is set to fail then you get EVENT_ABEND or EVENT_ABORT.

        This method makes it easy to know if this event is any of those.

        Returns:
        true if this is some kind of failure message

      • lite

        public TestEvent lite()
        Provide a new instance of TestEvent, cloned from this instance but with a longMsg field truncated to LITE_LONGMSG_LEN bytes. Useful to reduce memory requirements of GUIs.

        if this TestEvent already has a longMsg that is smaller than the threshold it will simply return a reference to itself.

        Suspicious {#link isSuspicious} and VSE {#link isVseEvent} events are never trimmed. Setting lisa property testexec.lite.longMsgLen to an integer will override the default (1024)

        Returns:
        a lite clone if necessary
        See Also:
        isSuspiciousEvent()
